{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565136"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17209"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17209"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.06,0.06,0.44,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9899"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95029"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9899"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78004"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2017"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23221"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46375"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95029"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of dry cough. The cough is worse at night and is not associated with sputum production or breathlessness. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, asthma, osteoarthritis and recently atrial fibrillation. Her medications include metoprolol, metformin, aspirin, apixaban, and paracetamol. She is a lifelong non-smoker and recently retired from working as a dental technician where she was exposed to acrylic dust. She has no pets at home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her chest is clear on auscultation. Nasal examination reveals normal mucosa with no polyps or discharge. Chest X-ray is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her chronic cough?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Beta blocker therapy","Post-nasal drip","Aspirin sensitivity","Occupational dust exposure","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a chronic dry cough of three months duration. Given her medication list and her history of asthma, this is most likely due to her beta blocker. \u003Cstrong\u003EBeta blocker therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause cough through bronchial hyperresponsiveness and increased airway reactivity. Beta blockers are generally contraindicated in patients with asthma as they can trigger bronchospasm and exacerbate asthma symptoms, including cough. The cough typically improves with cessation of the medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause chronic cough, particularly at night. However, there are no typical symptoms of reflux mentioned in the history, such as heartburn or regurgitation, making this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E can cause respiratory symptoms including cough, but this usually occurs as part of aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease (AERD) with associated asthma and nasal polyps, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-nasal drip\u003C/strong\u003E syndrome can cause chronic cough but typically presents with additional upper respiratory symptoms such as nasal congestion, rhinorrhoea, or throat clearing, which are absent here. The normal nasal examination makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccupational dust exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely as the patient is now retired from her work as a dental technician. While acrylic dust exposure could potentially cause respiratory symptoms, occupational causes typically improve when away from work, and her symptoms have developed after retirement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral medications can cause chronic cough through various mechanisms: ACE inhibitors (bradykinin accumulation), beta blockers (bronchial hyperresponsiveness), calcium channel blockers (enhanced cough reflex), NSAIDs (prostaglandin inhibition leading to bronchospasm in sensitive individuals), amiodarone (pulmonary toxicity), and methotrexate (pneumonitis). Beta blockers are especially likely to cause a chronic cough in patients with bronchial asthma due to their effect on beta-2 receptors in the airways, which can lead to bronchoconstriction. The appropriate management would be to trial cessation of metoprolol and switch to an alternative antihypertensive agent. If the cough resolves, this confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta blockers can cause chronic cough through bronchial hyperresponsiveness and are contraindicated in patients with asthma.","Many commonly prescribed medications can cause chronic cough through various mechanisms.","A trial of cessation or substitution of the suspected medication is diagnostic."],"references":["Smith JA, Woodcock A. Chronic cough. New England Journal of Medicine. 2016 Oct 20;375(16):1544-51.","De Blasio F, Virchow JC, Polverino M, Zanasi A, Behrakis PK, Kilin\u00e7 G, Balsamo R, De Danieli G, Lanata L. Cough management: a practical approach. Cough. 2011 Dec;7:1-2."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78004"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17209"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78004"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T21:24:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T21:24:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9899"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95029"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student a